TEXT(&beginproblem);
$showPartialCorrectAnswers = 1;

$a1 = random(19,30,1);
$b1 = random(3,7,1);
$c1 = random(8,12,1);
$c2 = random(1,3,1);
$c3 = $c1-$c2;
$a= $a1*1000;
$b = ($a1+$b1)*1000;
$b2 =$b*2;


TEXT(EV2(<<EOT));
A baseball team plays in he stadium that holds $b2 spectators. With the
ticket price at  $c1 the average attendence has been $a. When the price
dropped to $c3, the averege attendence rose to $b.  $BR
a) Find the demand function \( p(x) \), where \( x \) is the number of the 
spectators. (assume \(p(x) \) is linear)
\(p(x)= \)   \{ans_rule(30) \} $BR
b) How should be set  a ticket price to 
maximize  revenue? \{ans_rule(30) \} $BR
EOT

$ans1 ="($a-x)*$c2/($b1*1000) +$c1";
$ans2 = ($a*$c2/($b1*1000)+$c1)/2;

&ANS(function_cmp($ans1));
&ANS(std_num_cmp($ans2));

